  "message": "Message sent to team-lead's inbox",
  "routing": {
    "sender": "epistemology-expert",
    "senderColor": "yellow",
    "target": "@team-lead",
    "targetColor": "red",
    "summary": "\"Rightness\" — loaded in the right direction for 义",
    "content": "\"Rightness.\"\n\nI just argued that loaded English words serve the philosophical experiment — but that principle has a limit. The word needs to be loaded in the RIGHT direction. \"Righteousness\" is loaded with the WRONG associations.\n\n\"Righteousness\" in English activates a Judeo-Christian moral framework: divine command, moral absolutism, self-righteous judgment. When the author later deconstructs it, the reader will think \"ah, they're dismantling religious moralism\" — but that's not what the author is doing. The author treats 义 as a motivational bridge, a driving force between feeling and action. That's a phenomenological-practical concept, not a moral-theological one.\n\n\"Rightness\" is lighter, yes — but it's loaded in the correct direction. It suggests fitting action, appropriate response, getting-it-right. That's much closer to 义 as the impulse that translates inner humaneness into outward conduct. When the author deconstructs \"rightness,\" the reader will think about the adequacy of action to situation — which IS the author's concern.\n\nThe principle isn't \"use the most loaded word.\" It's \"use the word whose associations will be productively disrupted.\" \"Righteousness\" would be productively disrupted in a text about secularism or moral anti-realism. In a text about the motivational structure of ethical conduct, \"rightness\" is the word whose deconstruction teaches the reader something true about 义.\n\nKeep \"rightness.\""
  }
}
